<DOCNO> AP900430-0002 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
thousands of pelicans have died of 
starvation as an oasis in australias harsh outback country begins 
to dry up killing fish the birds feed on officials say 
it is unclear how many birds have died but the carcasses of 
thousands of adult birds and their chicks can be seen covering two 
islands in lake eyre in the northern part of south australia state 
the area is also dotted with unhatched eggs 
scientist say adult pelicans have been spotted flying up to 220 
miles a day in search of food 
an estimated 200000 pelicans made their homes at lake eyre a 
more than 100milelong body of water after the oasis waters 
swelled following heavy rains in october 
but drought followed the heavy rainfall increasing the salinity 
of the lake that killed large numbers of fish the pelicans eat 
causing starvation among the birds 
many pelicans have already left the area but few of the chicks 
were expected to survive said kim lowe national coordinator of 
the australian national parks and wildlife services 
birdmonitoring unit 
lowe said he was could not explain why the pelicans chose to 
nest at lake eyre 500 miles north of their nearest breeding ground 
it is an amazing phenomenon he said it is very humbling 
to think we havent got a basic idea why they would do this sort of 
thing 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

