<TEXT>
richard gephardt thinks maybe he was a little 
ahead of the curve on japan 
during the 1988 presidential campaign people accused him of 
bashing japan on its trade policies they called him a 
protectionist 
today however he says a lot more people are in his camp 
particularly democrats who sense a good issue for 1992 
there is a greater understanding on the part of a lot of 
people especially about our problems with japan and a few of the 
other countries where there are really significant trade access 
problems said the missouri democratic congressman 
president bush is receiving nearrecord high approval ratings in 
opinion polls but some analysts believe us trade problems with 
japan could emerge as an issue against the republican president in 
1992 
its the biggest longterm danger to the bush 
administration said democratic pollster stanley greenberg 
when bush announced friday he was removing japan from the hit 
list of countries judged by the administration to have the most 
offensive trade barriers against american products members of 
congress were quick to protest 
it is clear that japan should be on the list said sen 
donald riegle dmich our government is not using the tools that 
are available to correct this continuing hemorrhage of us capital 
and jobs 
trade access problems thats the polite term used by people 
upset by the 49 billion deficit in the us trade balance with 
japan some americans feeling the heat of competition with japan 
are apt to be less polite 
for example try the radio ad run by a suburban washington auto 
dealer 
in an accent distinctly japanese a man is heard admiring an 
american car at a fictitious tokyo auto show 
an incredulous american voice asks havent you ever seen a 
safford lincoln continental before 
only in magazines is the reply japanese have too many 
import restrictions and taxes to see one in person 
i wouldnt phrase it as japan bashing obviously said sen 
john breaux of louisiana chairman of the senate democratic 
campaign committee but i think it is a very legitimate issue 
people in the hinterlands and middle america are feeling we are 
giving away our technology 
there is a frustration americans feel over not controlling 
their own destiny said michael mccurry communications director 
of the democratic national committee 
but mccurry and other politicians questioned the longterm value 
of simply decrying japans trade practices 
bashing japan gets you the audience said the dnc official 
but you have to make a pretty sophisticated argument about what 
you would do 
ohio is one of the states where people feel hardest hit by 
competition from japan jim ruvolo the states democratic party 
chairman recalled that during the 1988 presidential campaign the 
ohio party produced and ran a television spot that directly 
attacked japanese trade practices 
when that ad ran democratic presidential nominee michael 
dukakis gained six points in the state 
frank greer a democratic political consultant said that among 
many americans there is anxiety we are slipping behind but he 
said people are as likely to blame american management practices as 
they are to point to japanese trade policies 
the japan bashing i dont think you can tell yet said bob 
teeter a republican pollster and adviser to bush i think its 
one of those things that has the potential on the surface to work 
for you and under the surface to backfire 
greenberg the democratic pollster has examined attitudes 
toward japan and said i dont think outandout bashing works 
any more you can run on putting our own house in order putting 
america first about watching out for our interests and not being 
taken advantage of and with japan as the primary example of a 
country that is taking advantage of our good will 
he said japan could become an issue against bush if there were 
an economic downturn 
i think the bush administration is seen as standing by while 
the japanese became more and more dominant would become a major 
political problem said greenberg 
attitudes toward japan differ 
in the midwest where the automobile industry has been hit hard 
politicians can attack japanese trade practices with impunity 
in california feelings are more complex 
i think theres a great concern about becoming too 
jingoistic said former california gov edmund g brown jr now 
the states democratic party chairman 
it may look good in a primary or a given state race but when 
you look at how imbedded we are in a world economy its going to be 
very difficult for somebody to get very far by bashing key elements 
of our own stability 
