<TEXT>
fed up with waiting for the bureaucracy to provide 
adequate housing a score of families has moved into a secondfloor 
conference room in a city government building 
vladimir i lenin kindeyed and smiling in the approved 
picture stares benevolently from the wall at a jumble of toddlers 
their bottles food packages piles of clothing and chairs pushed 
together for beds 
on april 15 the families took over the room in the government 
and communist party headquarters of moscows kiev district where 
lenins heirs have decided for generations what would be done for 
whom and when 
we wont leave here until each of us gets the key to a big 
new apartment said katya belyakova three of the children are 
hers 
the soviet housing shortage is severe a figure quoted often is 
that one in five people must share apartments 
president mikhail s gorbachev launched a muchheralded program 
several years ago to provide every citizen or family a private 
place to live by the year 2000 like many of his other reform 
schemes the plan has gone nowhere and the waiting list for 
apartments lengthens 
residents of many rundown apartments in central moscow are being 
moved to new buildings in other areas so the downtown structures 
can be renovated but building materials are anything but abundant 
mrs belyakova her husband and the children were sharing an 
apartment with three other families and the situation drove them to 
despair she said the other families quarrel over the use of the 
single toilet and other facilities and were pinching pushing and 
shouting at her children 
each family under lenins gaze in the 750squarefoot room has 
three or more children many russian couples have limited 
themselves to one or two because of the housing shortage so three 
or more is considered a family with many children 
the protesters are a mix of teachers laborers architects 
artists and engineers 
soviet law declares that the size of their families entitles 
them to new housing no more than three years after they apply but 
many of the protesters have been crowded five or more to a room for 
years 
at the square white kiev district office building children run 
in the halls while parents draft statements seek meetings with 
