<TEXT>
the supreme court today let stand a ruling 
that says the public has no constitutional right to know the names 
of jurors while they are serving in a criminal trial 
the court without comment rejected a challenge to a delaware 
judges order that kept jurors names secret during a 
muchpublicized murder trial 
lawyers for gannett co inc publisher of the news journal in 
wilmington said the judges order contradicts previous supreme 
court rulings on the publics right of access to criminal trials 
the delaware supreme court saying those previous rulings do not 
apply to the release of jurors names upheld the judges order 
last nov 13 
gannett has failed to carry its burden of establishing any 
historical tradition of constitutional dimension regarding public 
access to jurors names the state supreme court ruled 
the dispute stemmed from the wilmington murder trial of steven 
pennell who was charged with the serial torture slayings of three 
women state prosecutors sought the death penalty 
pennell was convicted of two of the murders and was sentenced 
to life in prison 
before the trials jury selection began the presiding judge 
ordered that potential jurors be identified in open court by 
numbers not their names throughout the trial only the judge 
prosecutors the defendant and his lawyers knew the jurors names 
the newsjournal had published an article offering biographical 
sketches of all the jurors in a thenrecently concluded murder 
trial and the judge was concerned the newspaper might run a 
similar article during pennells trial 
jurors were not to be sequestered and the judge said he was 
worried jurors might be harassed during the trial interfering in 
pennells right to an impartial jury 
lawyers for gannett noted that jurors had not been sequestered 
in the previous trial and that none was harassed after being 
identified in the newspaper 
but names of jurors in pennells case were not made public until 
his trial ended 
in a landmark 1980 ruling the nations highest court said the 
public has a constitutional right to attend criminal trials even 
when defendants object the justices since have expanded that 
ruling to cover jury selection and pretrial proceedings in criminal 
cases 
judges cannot abridge that right the court has said without 
articulating the compelling interests to be served by secrecy 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for gannett said by 
cloaking jurors in anonymity the bond between the jury and the 
public is weakened hearing the name of each juror called and 
relating that name to the jurors testimony during jury selection 
insures public confidence that the process is fair and the answers 
are truthful 
the delaware supreme court rejected those arguments 
contrary to the rather pietistic claims of gannett and other 
news organizations there is nothing to suggest that such actions 
undermined public trust in the judicial system the state court 
said 
delaware attorney general charles oberly iii urged the justices 
to reject gannetts appeal the conduct of the trial judge here 
did not undermine the goal of ensuring governmental 
accountability he said 
the case is gannett vs delaware 891324 
</TEXT>
