<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to let 
colorado prosecutors use as trial evidence incriminating statements 
made by a man charged with the menacing use of a deadly weapon 
the attorneys general of 22 states had urged the justices to use 
the case to clarify just when police must give socalled miranda 
warnings before questioning criminal suspects 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that also blocked 
prosecutors use as evidence of a rifle seized from the home of the 
man charles cleburn of fremont county colo 
deputy sheriff don adler went to cleburns home sept 7 1988 
to investigate a report that someone matching cleburns description 
had menaced a young man with a rifle 
adler and a deputy who accompanied him were uniformed and armed 
adler who was on friendly terms with cleburn engaged him in 
what a state trial judge called sort of a good ol boy 
scenario 
cleburn was asked whether he had had a runin with a young man 
and whether he owned a rifle similar to the one the young man had 
described 
adler then asked cleburn to show him the rifle but said you 
dont have to let me 
cleburn made certain incriminating remarks while answering 
adlers questions and later agreed to let the deputy take the 
rifle 
after walking to his car with the rifle the deputy changed his 
mind about what to do he walked back to the house asked cleburn 
to come outside and arrested him 
prior to telling cleburn he was under arrest adler did not tell 
him of his right to remain silent or to get a lawyers help before 
answering any questions 
since its famous miranda vs arizona decision in 1966 the 
supreme court has required police to give such warnings before 
questioning criminal suspects who are in custody 
a state trial judge ruled that cleburns comments and the seized 
rifle could not be used as evidence against him and the colorado 
supreme court voted 43 to uphold that ruling last nov 20 
the state supreme court rejected prosecutors arguments that 
cleburn was not in custody when he made the incriminating 
remarks 
the state court also ruled that cleburn had not voluntarily 
given the rifle to adler by that time cleburn had nothing to 
lose the state court said 
the prior relationship between one of the deputies and the 
defendant made the questioning subtly coercive the defendant was 
in custody and the defendant had already made incriminating 
statements without the benefit of a miranda advisement the state 
court said 
the november ruling was appealed by district attorney edward j 
rogers iii and supported in a friendofthecourt brief 
submitted by colorado attorney general duane woodward and signed by 
the attorneys general of 20 other states 
citing general confusion over what amounts to police custody 
they told the court definitive guidance is needed regarding what 
type of seizure is necessary to trigger miranda protections 
the 20 states are alabama delaware florida idaho illinois 
iowa indiana kansas maine massachusetts mississippi missouri 
new hampshire north carolina ohio south carolina vermont 
washington west virginia and wyoming 
the case is colorado vs cleburn 891232 
</TEXT>
