<TEXT>
seven months after hurricane hugo smashed 
into south carolina the flow of relief supplies has slowed to a 
trickle and the federal government has shuttered its disaster 
centers 
but mennonites are still helping 
farmers carpenters and professionals from such places as 
newton kan goshen ind and lancaster pa are giving their 
time and talents to help south carolinians recover from the states 
worst natural disaster in nearly a century 
were not here for the glory we get out of it were here 
because people need us said wilbur lentz coordinator of the 
mennonite disaster services relief effort one of the biggest 
blessings has been to see one of these poor people back in a house 
and to see that great big smile 
jesus said that if you see one of these people in need and 
dont do anything about it how can you say gods love is in you 
hugos 135 mph winds smashed ashore on sept 21 killing 29 
people and causing about 59 billion property damage 
after the storm up to 300 volunteers a week responded to calls 
by the mennonite church to help with cleanup and repairs 
that number has tapered off but about 100 mennonites continue 
to work each week lentz of akron pa said the operation will 
continue at least through years end 
a lot of our volunteers are farmers and tradesmen and they 
have their own jobs to attend to now said lentz an ordained 
minister and carpenter who has been in south carolina since fall 
officials estimate that perhaps 3000 mennonites have worked on 
storm recovery about one for every congregation in north america 
the denomination has about 325000 members whose beliefs include 
opposition to holding public office they also favor plain dress 
but unlike the amish who split from them in the 17th century 
mennonites accept reliance on some modern conveniences 
volunteers donate their time and provide their own 
transportation and donations are used to help feed and house them 
at disaster sites 
its very much a part of the faith of the mennonites said 
sandy weaver a spokeswoman for mennonite disaster service at the 
groups headquarters in akron near lancaster pa 
mennonites disaster efforts were as an outgrowth of world war 
ii as conscientious objectors they performed community service 
rather than fight afterward some wondered why they provided 
service just in wartime she said 
congregations in the midwest responded to disasters in the early 
1950s and the disaster service agency was established in 1955 
in south carolina the mennonites supply free labor and 
materials are either donated or provided through insurance money 
the most discouraging thing for me is deciding who you help 
and who you dont help said vic plessinger a volunteer from 
smithville ohio who has been here since march 
the group receives referrals from the american red cross and 
social service agencies helping those who lack the money to cover 
costs of repairs or rebuilding 
since hugo mennonites have repaired hundreds of roofs and 
rebuilt more than a dozen homes 
among the beneficiaries is juanita singleton whose house near 
pineville 30 miles north of charleston was destroyed 
