the united states will suspend trade benefits 
for liberia on july 1 but will allow thailand and indonesia to 
continue to participate despite charges they have violated workers 
rights a trade official said monday 
the bush administration found that liberia had not taken steps 
to better its record but that the two asian countries had 
according to the official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
about 130 areas in the third world were allowed last year to 
ship 10 billion worth of goods to the united states dutyfree or 
at reduced rates of duty the measures encourage imports from those 
areas because the lower duties make them cheaper and more 
attractive to importers than goods from competing countries 
auto equipment such as tires brakes and storage batteries are 
among the major imported items the program is being expanded and 
is expected to grow by at least 500 million this year 
other major importing countries have similar preference programs 
us labor organizations had complained that some governments 
violated internationally recognized workers rights by using child 
labor restricting the formation of labor unions and other 
measures us law requires suspending privileges for those 
countries 
a statement issued by trade representative carla hills said 
another year will be taken to review the cases against syria 
benin the dominican republic haiti and nepal 
romania nicaragua and burma remain suspended panama was 
reinstated earlier this year and poland and hungary were added to 
the list after the end of hardline communist rule there 
other eastern european countries are expected to follow and 
nicaragua is likely to be reinstated the official said 
new products will be made eligible from bolivia colombia 
ecuador and peru as part of the bush administrations decision to 
help wean them away from traffic in drugs 
