<DOCNO> AP900430-0114 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the nations couch potatoes say 
watching television is mindless boring addictive and takes less 
concentration than any activity short of sleep 
americans will spend an average of two hours per day the 
equivalent of seven years over a lifetime sitting in front of the 
tube according to a 13year study of viewers released monday 
viewers in the study reported their hours in front of the tube 
made them feel worse rather than better but like drug users 
struggling to kick an unwanted addiction they have a hard time 
pulling the plug 
a viscous cycle can develop wherein viewing begets more 
viewing said the studys coauthor robert kubey a rutgers 
university psychologist both the realization and escape that 
television so readily provides also leads many viewers to become 
dependent on the medium 
kubey and mihaly csikszentmihalyi of the university of chicago 
published their findings in a book television and the quality of 
life how viewing shapes everyday experience 
and while many turn to the tube to feel better they usually 
wind up feeling worse after a dose of news cop shows and sitcoms 
viewers said they become more drowsy bored sadder lonelier and 
hostile the more they watch 
the misery is a sort of family activity the researchers found 
while television generally increases the total time that 
family members spend together it tends to reduce their interaction 
with one another and they spend a disproportionate amount of this 
time together in a passive mode kubey said 
spokesmen from abc and nbc said they were looking at information 
from the study and werent ready to comment a cbs spokeswoman did 
not immediately return a telephone call seeking comment 
howard gardner a psychologist at harvard university said the 
project is seen as one of the most inclusive analyses on the 
effects of television among thousands of studies on the medium 
to assess viewing patterns and the impact they have on mood the 
researchers said they looked at viewers in a different way than in 
previous studies 
instead of asking them to recall events or take tests in a 
laboratory csikszentmihalyi and kubey asked 1200 people ranging 
from age 10 to 82 to carry beepers and to write down how they felt 
every time it went off 
basically csikszentmihalyi said we collected a series of 
snapshots of what people were doing and how they felt at the time 
we were thus able to map moods and patterns of behavior that 
may have eluded the subjects themselves 
the researchers discovered a perverse sort of benefit from the 
tvinduced trance 
certainly it can be argued that using television in this 
manner habitually is no worse and may indeed be better than 
habitually using alcohol or other moodaltering substances 
</TEXT>
