<TEXT>
jury selection began monday for the trial 
of a man who faces a possible life prison sentence if convicted of 
poisoning a famous centuriesold oak tree 
paul stedman cullen 46 is accused of pouring the herbicide 
velpar around the base of the treaty oak where according to 
folklore stephen f austin signed a treaty with indians in the 
1820s austin is regarded as the father of texas 
the poisoning was discovered memorial day half of the 60foot 
tree has died despite 100000 in donations and herculean efforts 
to save it officials have said 
the act shocked residents and touched people around the country 
many sent getwell cards to the tree or stopped to write messages 
and leave tokens at its base 
workers have severed the most severely affected roots and have 
injected sugar water in hopes of diluting the poison 
cullen of elroy was charged with felony criminal mischief and 
has been in jail without bail for more than 10 months he could be 
sentenced to life in prison if convicted because he has a prior 
burglary conviction 
police and prosecutors have never detailed the suspected motive 
when cullen was arrested on june 29 1989 an arrest warrant 
alleged the poisoning was part of a ritual 
sgt john jones who investigated the case refused to elaborate 
the austin americanstatesman reported before his arrest that a 
suspect in the case was trying to cast a spell in a romantic matter 
said jones the occults really got nothing to do with it 
hes charged with damaging the tree normally what we have to 
prove is intentionally and knowingly damaging property we dont 
necessarily have to prove why he did it 
attorneys expect the trial to last about two weeks 
cullen also could face up to 15 years in prison for federal 
charges of possession of a firearm by a felon and making a false 
statement to a firearms dealer the charges stem from a 22caliber 
rifle that police say was found in his truck when he was arrested 
