<TEXT>
women loaning men money is commonplace 
nowadays but in firstcentury egypt that meant marriage 
university of michigan researchers recently deciphered documents 
suggesting women in ancient egypt made shortterm loans to their 
prospective mates to guarantee their fidelity before and during 
marriage 
the 22 documents deciphered by classical studies professor 
ludwig koenen and two assistants recorded the business and legal 
transactions of the pausiris family the family lived about 70 ad 
in oxyrhynchos then a major city under roman rule 
the documents include several loan receipts made out to dioskous 
pausiris by thermouthis his wife of one year 
thermouthis probably came from a lowermiddleclass family and 
couldnt afford a dowry to secure a marriage contract koenen said 
such women instead obtained financial security by loaning their 
fiances small amounts of money he said 
researchers at the ann arbor school deciphered evidence that 
thermouthis loaned a small amount to dioskous for two months 
shortly before they married 
although none of the documents described the couples personal 
relationship one a canceled loan receipt dated about a year 
after the marriage indicates dioskous repaid a second larger 
loan then got a divorce 
where did he get the money perhaps he had a good business 
year but a cynic would suspect that he had found another lady who 
would give him a loan koenen speculated 
the researchers findings will be published this summer the 
university said 
</TEXT>
