<TEXT>
two greenpeace activists climbed 150 feet up the 
georgiapacific building on monday and unfurled a banner to protest 
the companys use of chlorine in the manufacture of paper pulp 
a 30by12 foot banner reading take the poison out of pulp 
was unfurled after the climbers reached the 13th floor of the 
52story building about 830 am the building was chosen because 
atlantabased georgiapacific is the largest pulp operator in the 
nation a greenpeace spokesman said 
about 200 passersby stopped to watch the fivehour protest 
which coincided with the release in washington of an environmental 
protection agency report on dioxins found in bleached paper 
the epa said the amount of dioxin in such items as milk cartons 
and toilet tissue is too small to pose a health hazard but the 
agency is concerned about dioxin contamination of waterways near 
some paper mills 
the issue is not dioxin but chlorine it is an unnecessary 
raw material in paper production said greenpeace spokesman brian 
hunt 
several european nations have already made the conversion to 
nonchlorine bleaching processes that yield highquality 
highwhiteness paper were here to encourage georgiapacific to 
take the chlorine out of pulp he said 
beth zoffmann a georgiapacific spokeswoman said chlorine 
produces only a minute quantity of dioxin and added we believe 
our products are safe 
pointing up at the two protesters she said this creates a 
far greater risk than the entire production of dioxin in pulp they 
are creating an unnecessary risk to themselves and the people on 
the ground there is no need for that showmanship type activity 
police arrested the pair identified by greenpeace as dj 
lachappelle 24 of washington dc and laurel greenberg 31 of 
boston after they descended police said they would be charged 
with criminal trespass and reckless conduct but no charges were 
filed immediately 
