<TEXT>
chinese authorities lifted martial law on tuesday 
in the tibetan capital of lhasa nearly 14 months after the 
restrictions were imposed to quell bloody nationalist rioting 
china said social order had been restored 
the official xinhua news agency said martial law imposed march 
8 1989 after three days of antichinese rioting officially ended 
on orders of premier li peng 
in view of the fact that the situation in lhasa has become 
stable and social order has returned to normal the task of 
enforcing martial law in the city has been successfully 
fulfilled said a cabinet order signed by li 
xinhua said peoples liberation army troops were ordered to 
leave their posts around the jokhang temple buddhist tibets 
holiest shrine and a flashpoint for antigovernment demonstrations 
at midnight monday 
troops have manned checkpoints on main roads leading into the 
temple and maintained sentries around the barkhor square that 
encompasses the temple 
it is likely that the army and the paramilitary peoples armed 
police will continue to be deployed in large numbers around the 
city 
antichinese proindependence sentiments remain high in lhasa 
xinhua warned monday that separatists on both sides of the border 
are still plotting to continue their separatist and destructive 
activities we absolutely cannot relax our vigilance 
the government said 16 people were killed and more than 100 
wounded in last years riots tibetan and foreign sources said 
about 30 died 
altogether tibetans say about 70 people have died in clashes 
with police and soldiers in the past three years 
the rioting was the bloodiest in tibet since a failed 1959 
uprising and marked the first time martial law was announced in 
china since the 196676 cultural revolution when radical leftists 
tried to purge china of bourgeois influence 
the riots began march 5 when tibetans carrying banners marched 
around jokhang temple chinese police opened fire 
angry crowds began stoning police and went on a threeday 
rampage burning chinese shops and attacking chinese passersby 
police responded with more gunfire and tear gas 
tibetans spoke of hundreds of arrests after the march riots but 
chinas official media reported only 20 people being sentenced 
some receiving life prison terms and others a few years 
during martial law the military presence in lhasa normally 
high was stepped up further with soldiers or paramilitary 
officers stationed at intersections most reporters were barred 
from the city tourism was tightly restricted 
nonetheless reports of several small nationalist protests have 
filtered out to be routinely denied by the chinese 
most recently a monitoring group in london the tibet 
information network said chinese authorities expelled several 
buddhist monks and nuns from religious institutions and hundreds of 
monks left their monasteries in protest 
most monks and nuns remain loyal to the dalai lama their exiled 
religious leader and once tibets secular ruler they have been at 
the forefront of most independence demonstrations in recent years 
and were forced to undergo political education during martial law 
china has said the dalai lama who won the 1989 nobel peace 
prize for his peaceful resistance to chinese rule can return only 
if he gives up his proposal for tibetan autonomy he fled to india 
in 1959 
china says its sovereignty over tibet dates back to the 13th 
century when a chinese princess married a tibetan ruler 
however many tibetans say chinese rule was sporadic and that 
for many years tibetans had their own theocratic government flag 
and currency tibetans speak a different language and they are 
culturally distinct from chinese 
</TEXT>
