<TEXT>
a summary of developments in the news industry for the week of 
april 2330 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
an electronic darkroom system designed by the 
associated press to replace its current network of photo receivers 
is on schedule and meeting preproduction testing goals ap 
president and general manager louis d boccardi told the annual 
meeting of the news cooperative 
boccardi told publishers and editors representing the aps 1486 
newspaper members on april 23 that fullscale installation of the 
ap leaf darkroom is to begin in september after summer 
fieldtesting an installation schedule is to be announced in june 
because installation of the darkroom will mean conversion to 
satellite delivery the schedule will be driven by where ap can 
achieve the biggest savings in landline costs to help pay for the 
project boccardi said 
he said a joint committee of member photo editors and production 
executives would be announced within two weeks to advise the ap on 
the rollout of the darkroom program bill rinehart the 
justretired anpa vice president for technical matters will serve 
on the panel 
boccardi compared the new technology for electronic handling of 
photos to the computer terminal revolution in handling words he 
said it will mark a major step forward for newspapers 
we will train your staff and aps service reliability will 
stand behind the ap leaf darkroom it is the right step at the 
right time boccardi said 
he noted that darkrooms from sources other than ap could be used 
with the ap leaf which will fully conform to anpa standards 
other technological advancements are imminent boccardi added 
by july 1 the ap expects to complete the conversion of its 
entire highspeed system to deliver copy to members at 9000 words a 
minute 
a customized stocks service that allows members to localize 
market table pages is in print in a dozen member newspapers and 
the installation schedule for selectstocks will be accelerated 
through the rest of the year 
boccardi also touched on the plight of terry anderson chief 
middle east correspondent who was taken hostage in lebanon five 
years ago last month 
we continue to search for an end to his ordeal and pray that 
recent optimistic comments will lead to his release boccardi 
said 
</TEXT>
