<TEXT>
an advertising consultant told the american 
newspaper publishers association on april 24 that papers should 
adopt a more local focus because issues such as the push for 
independence in lithuania wont sell ads 
at the associations 104th annual convention the nations 
newspaper publishers also discussed declining readership 
telecommunications developments affecting papers and recycling of 
newsprint 
the only specialized thing about a newspaper is its 
locality said laurel cutler vice chairman of fcbleber katz 
partners and vice president of consumer affairs for the chrysler 
corp 
frank a daniels jr president and publisher of the news amp 
observer of raleigh nc said a newspaper traditionally has 
been a smorgasbord you have something in there for everybody 
but ms cutler warned against newspapers trying to be all 
things to all people and suggested specialization was more 
appealing to advertisers 
the more generalized the more all things to all people the 
less we care about you she said 
the comments came during a panel discussion called ozzie and 
harriet are gone who do you think youre writing for 
virginia dodge fielder vice president of research for 
knightridder inc expressed industry frustration in trying to 
pinpoint the cause of declining readership 
i wish people hated us more she said i wish they 
expressed more dissatisfaction because if they did wed know how to 
tackle it what the public is saying is not i hate you but i 
dont need you youre a great electric company but i live in an 
allgas house 
one publisher said the industry may be close to winning a 
6yearold fight with the bell companies over who can transmit 
electronic information in the future 
robert m johnson publisher president andchief executive 
officer of newsday inc of melville ny reported that congress 
is likely to pass a bill soon setting a telecommunications public 
policy 
he said the bell companies have set aside a 25 million war 
chest to fight for the right to publish information on its 
electronic circuits he said bell seeks to launch an electronic 
yellow pages that would compete directly with newspaper 
advertising 
such actions would violate a 1984 federal court decision that 
set out the principle of diversity in dividing atampt into separate 
companies he said 
citing antitrust laws us district judge harold greene held 
that those who control telecommunication lines should not also 
control the information that goes over those lines johnson said 
johnson said that in the past year a task force of the anpa has 
worked with congress on legislation addressing the issue a draft 
bill was produced but has not yet been passed an appeal of the 
original federal order has sent that back to greene for 
reconsideration 
the chairman of the anpas newsprint resource task force said 
publishers should move quickly to recycle newsprint to keep the 
government from imposing regulations 
frank a bennack jr president and chief executive officer of 
the hearst corp new york said publishers have resolved to double 
the amount of recycled newsprint used in the coming year reaching 
a total of 46 million tons 
we believe efforts to control newsprint can mean efforts to 
control the press he said the prospect of dealing with a 
regulated newsprint industry calls up an array of terrifying 
unknowns 
bennack said that at least two states have already mandated that 
newspapers use recycled newsprint but he insisted such official 
orders will be unnecessary if publishers act on the recycling issue 
voluntarily 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the st louis sun folded april 25 ending a 
sevenmonth struggle to become the countrys first bigcity 
newspaper to make a profitable launch since world war ii 
it is clear that we could not achieve sufficient circulation 
to make this enterprise viable and so we have concluded that there 
is no longer room in st louis for the sun said ralph ingersoll 
ii editor in chief 
with a circulation of about 100000 the sevenday morning 
tabloid never threatened the st louis postdispatchs circulation 
of 375000 daily and 565000 on sunday but it did manage to 
generate a fair share of controversy 
the sun was accused of sensationalism for its coverage of a 
politician involved in a sexual assault and of the fiveyear 
anniversary of an accident in which a man was nearly sawed in two 
the newspaper also was chided for running photos of revealing 
womens swimsuits and lingerie some critics derided its flood of 
promotions fluorescent green billboards and contests 
but the sun was praised for its coverage of the effort to build 
a new domed stadium downtown and of the troubles facing st louis 
major air carrier trans world airlines 
ingersoll is chairman and chief executive of ingersoll 
publications co and has an interest in four other newspaper 
holding companies he said his new tabloid needed to sell most of 
its copies from vending boxes and newsracks 
instead it ended up with homedelivery sales outnumbering 
singlecopy sales 2to1 
that cost the paper which spent more than 25 million to start 
up an unexpected 5 million home delivery costs are higher 
because of the expenses of billing customers and hiring delivery 
people 
the sudden death did not surprise everyone 
they read the handwriting on the wall the weather was 
good the cardinals were playing the blues were playing and people 
still werent buying the paper you dont have to be a brain 
surgeon to figure it out said kevin horrigan a columnist who 
jumped ship from the st louis postdispatch to join the sun 
in horrigans old newsroom postdispatch editor william woo 
said he was sorry about the demise of the sun the sun undertook 
a difficult mission and made a valiant effort which fell short 
woo said 
ingersoll said he didnt know how much money overall he had lost 
on the sun he said the decision to close had nothing to do with 
debt problems at another of his newspaper companies 
i emphasize the sole reason the st louis sun did not succeed 
was the inability to generate adequate singlecopy sales he said 
on april 20 an offer by ingersoll to buy back much of the 240 
million of junk bonds issued by his community newspapers inc 
failed to attract a single bondholder if the company cant agree 
with bondholders on a buyback it could be forced to more than 
double the interest rate on some of the bonds to more than 26 
percent 
the st louis sun was owned by ingersoll newspapers inc which 
also owns 77 other newspapers in seven states 
when he launched the sun in september ingersoll said he wanted 
to prove that new newspapers if properly designed and promoted 
could be introduced in the united states just as they had been in 
other countries 
he said he was planning to move to st louis and would 
personally direct the papers launch he spent many late nights in 
its hightech newsroom learning about sophisticated equipment and 
refining the papers look 
im disappointed i feel that we gave it our very best shot 
he said 
