<TEXT>
like the entire newspaper industry 
gannett co inc is mired in a recession that began in the second 
half of 1989 chairman john j curley told shareholders april 26 
gannett whose profits grew along with its increasing size for 
22 consecutive years since it became a publicly traded company 
managed to report an up quarter but barely in its 
firstquarter earnings report curley said 
curleys comments were made after the american newspaper 
publishers association meeting at which news executives discussed 
the general drop in advertising revenues and an accompanying 
decline in readership 
gannett has suffered from the downturn in advertising that 
started in the northeast spread to the south and has not yet 
reached the west coast company officials said they were cautious 
about prospects for their papers including usa today 
still they said they expect usa today to turn profitable for 
the first time in 1990 they also said usa weekend is approaching 
profitability and now carries more ads than its main competitor 
parade magazine 
but curley cautioned we wont really know about the retail 
climate until we find out what happens in may and june 
he noted that gannetts stock price rose along with the fortunes 
of the company in the first half of 1989 then fell when the 
newspaper business turned down in mid1989 
trustees of the gannett foundation whose sole asset is 10 
percent of the companys stock said april 25 they would put the 
