times mirror corp said april 25 its 
firstquarter profit fell 33 percent largely because of an 
advertising slowdown that hit its northeastern newspapers consumer 
magazines and broadcast tv operations 
for the quarter ending april 1 times mirrors earnings fell to 
46 million or 36 cents per share down from 688 million or 53 
cents per share a year earlier 
revenues rose 33 percent to 8752 million from 8469 million 
but times mirror said its slide in earnings was partly 
attributable to higher promotional costs and higher circulation 
that pushed up operating costs at the los angeles times 
although our professional publishing and cable television 
operations achieved solid earnings growth during the quarter their 
performance only partially offset the marked deterioration in our 
newspaper publishing segment said robert f erburu times 
mirrors chairman and chief executive 
ad volume was slow at the northeastern newspapers with newsday 
and new york newsday suffering from a depressed new york economy 
times mirror said the 1990 first quarter also had one less sunday 
than the yearearlier period which reduced revenues 
despite increased revenues at the los angeles times a surge in 
circulation increased operating costs contributing to a 38 percent 
decline in operating profit from newspapers 
times mirror said its companywide circulation as reported to 
the audit bureau of circulations but not yet verified rose 41 
percent for the daily papers and 32 percent on sunday over the 
past six months 
