<TEXT>
the minnesota house voted unanimously 
april 23 for a bill that places further limits on the ability of 
governmental bodies to hold closed meetings 
the legislation was drafted in response to a state supreme court 
ruling last year that said meetings must be closed when information 
classified as private under the states data practices act is 
discussed 
the ruling required local governmental bodies to close the 
meeting and kick out the public and kick out the media when they 
wanted to discuss private data said rep phil carruthers who 
helped draft the new law 
that meant that a lot of meetings were being closed that 
really didnt need to be and it seemed inappropriate inconsistent 
with the idea of the open meeting law he said 
the new legislation prohibits local governmental units from 
closing meetings to discuss private data with some exceptions 
such as when it would identify alleged victims of criminal sexual 
conduct 
the bill also says that during an open meeting a public body 
shall make reasonable efforts to protect private data from public 
disclosure for instance it suggests that local officials protect 
the identity of some people by using a number or letter of the 
alphabet when referring to them 
it lays out the specifics of which prevails openness or 
privacy in which types of circumstances so i think it will be a 
lot easier for local governments to deal with and a lot easier for 
the public and for the media carruthers said 
the minnesota newspaper association was a key backer of the new 
bill which passed the house 1280 and the senate 460 
</TEXT>
