<TEXT>
a federal commission studying the 
mississippi delta region for 18 months will offer a roadmap for 
slow gradual economic improvement when it issues its final report 
to congress next week 
the lower mississippi delta development commission will call for 
greater regional cooperation such as environmental compacts and 
university research consortiums extra help in steering kids to 
college leadership training to change entrenched attitudes 
that have held the delta back and some government aid 
despite stressing the need for more help from the federal 
government govs bill clinton of arkansas buddy roemer of 
louisiana and ray mabus of mississippi all of whom serve on the 
ninemember commission say they wont be asking for a quickfix or 
a vast new dealtype program 
if there is a peace dividend you want to invest in 
america why not start here roemer said 
the work of this commission is not about handouts though 
its about giving choices and some options to people who too often 
feel they have none he said 
added wilbur hawkins the federal commissions executive 
director we bail out the savings and loans we send millions to 
poland and to panama i just dont want this nation for the first 
time in its history to say we cant help the unfortunate 
the memphisbased commission has not been without controversy 
black leaders reacted angrily when all nine panelists appointed 
were white men even though onethird of the deltas population is 
black hawkins hired after the uproar is black 
the commission which has spent 3 million on its study was 
modeled after past federal bodies appointed to deal with regional 
problems such as the tennessee valley authority and the 
appalachian regional commission 
but clinton the commission chairman said he believes the 
document released may 14 will be unique in government 
it will literally be a handbook for a decade of action he 
said we want a report that says what the national government is 
supposed to do what the state governments are supposed to do the 
local governments and the private sector 
tourism will be one area the commission hopes to help develop 
officials said marketing will be another some on the commission 
hope for a common markettype cooperation among the states and 
perhaps even a mississippi delta logo and promotional campaign for 
local products 
people on wall street see more attractive investments in 
venezuela than in the mississippi delta and thats a marketing 
problem said stan hyland a memphis state university 
anthropologist working on the commission staff 
weve got to put in place incentives to bring our youth back 
home and our capital back home hawkins said 
we cant just afford to take a bandaid approach 
</TEXT>
