<TEXT>
counties included in the mississippi delta 
region have long held the dubious distinction of having some of 
americas poorest and most troubled schools illiteracy and dropout 
rates are high money is scarce and the legacy of a troubled racial 
past compounds the problems but in recent years several states 
have made education reform a priority this second report in a 
fiveday ap extra series children of the delta examines one 
tennessee school district struggling to break the cycle of failure 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
when warner dickerson strides the 
school halls in this poor patch of tennessee he confronts the 
traditions that rend young lives 
he sees girls whove become mothers too soon and boys wholl 
give up on school too early the children of men and women who 
mostly grew up the same way 
a new generation an old predicament a common denominator 
if you had to sum it up with a word or expression its 
poverty said dickerson superintendent of the fayette county 
schools your morality is different your longrange planning is 
different you just live from day to day you dont plan ahead 
babies having babies illiteracy among parents not having 
jobs its all here 
such problems have paralyzed the mississippi delta region which 
includes parts of arkansas illinois kentucky louisiana 
mississippi missouri and tennessee many of them home to some of 
americas poorest and most troubled schools 
mississippi has consistently ranked lowest in the nation on 
standardized test scores kentucky ranks at the bottom in 
percentage of high school graduates 
