<TEXT>
 
editors note it all began in another century when the 
delicacy of the east met the chutzpah of the west japan wanted 
mainly to be left alone until the united states started 
interfering then uncle sam after world war ii set about rebuilding 
a country it had helped to crush a country that now has become its 
strongest economic competitor its a story of ironies 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
on july 8 1853 americans went calling on the japanese who had 
sealed themselves off from the world for centuries they werent 
glad to see us 
on dec 7 1941 the japanese came calling on americans we 
werent at all glad to see them 
in 1947 six years after the attack on pearl harbor a group of 
american businessmen went to tokyo at the behest of their 
government to see if japans devastated economy could be brought to 
life they found ways 
now in 1990 hat in hand american officials confer anxiously 
with the japanese once again in the hope of persuading them to open 
their gates 
it has been you might say a strange relationship a classic 
study in irony 
it was the united states that opened japan and brought it 
into the global marketplace in 1853 until then for two and a half 
centuries the country was so fiercely private that foreign sailors 
shipwrecked on its shores werent allowed to leave and japanese 
sailors thrown up on foreign shores werent allowed to come home 
today little shy remote reclusive japan is resoundingly no 
longer any of the above japanese investors are as ubiquitous as 
japanese tourists they are into everything from the skating rink 
at rockefeller center in new york to the sistine chapel in the 
vatican 
today 137 years after an american sailor persuaded them to 
trade the japanese sell 49 billion more of their products in the 
united states than the united states sells in japan today japan 
joins the united states in having the two largest economies in the 
world and in sharing onethird of the worlds total output of goods 
and services 
this munificence began in a remarkable comic opera in which the 
fragile delicacy of the east was introduced to the chutzpah of the 
west 
on that day in 1853 commodore matthew calbraith perry sailed up 
tokyo bay in four black warships belching black smoke the japanese 
had never seen steamers before they thought these were floating 
volcanoes 
local officials came aboard to tell the intruders to state their 
business and be gone perry said he would talk to no one of minor 
rank a vice governor came out perry wouldnt see him the 
governor came and perry let it be known through subordinates that 
he would meet with a japanese prince ashore to transmit a letter 
from president millard fillmore to the emperor of japan and unless 
it was delivered the united states of america would be gravely 
insulted 
agreed but not without ceremony the japanese built a pavilion 
festooned with beautiful silks to receive the letter they lined 
the shore with 5000 soldiers and then flanked by two armed 
gigantic blacks perry landed with 100 sailors 100 marines and 
three ships bands playing hail columbia 
with bows all around he delivered the letter which was 
inscribed on vellum bound in blue velvet sealed in a rosewood box 
trimmed in gold and signed by your good friend millard 
fillmore who apparently made friends easily perry said he would 
be back next year for the emperors answer and sailed off 
back he came on feb 11 1854 this time with seven ships and 
gifts of sets of freshly invented telegraph instruments a 
quartersize steam locomotive capable of 20 mph and complete with 
cars and tracks four volumes of audubons birds of america an 
assortment of farm tools and guns a barrel of whiskey and several 
cases of champagne 
thus was the east won the emperor signed a treaty agreeing to 
limited trade the safe return of shipwrecked american sailors and 
the use of two ports as coal stations japan had joined the world 
having fought foreign influences it now embraced them it sent 
students bureaucrats and businessmen abroad to learn from the west 
and imported western teachers at high salaries to teach its young 
it erected factories encouraged foreign trade and built a strong 
army and navy 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900430-0185 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
and soon japan which for centuries wouldnt risk life beyond 
its own islands now decided it couldnt survive on them alone it 
reached out for markets and raw materials the way the west did and 
with two wars only 10 years apart against china and russia it 
carved an empire on the mainland of asia 
with 61 other countries it renounced war as an instrument of 
national policy in 1928 and three years later renounced the 
renouncement it marched again in china and manchuria in the hunt 
for new markets and fodder for its growing war machine 
finally its strategists concluded only one obstacle stood 
between japan and the rubber of indochina the bauxite and tin of 
malaya and burma and the oil of the dutch east indies and so the 
former recluse and pupil charged through the door perry had opened 
and attacked the united states at pearl harbor while its 
negotiators talked peace in washington 
the war it thus started cost japan 1972000 lives military and 
civilian and killed 98211 americans it brought japan the shame 
of its first surrender to a foreign invader douglas macarthur 
riding through tokyo on a road lined with 30000 japanese soldiers 
their backs to the conqueror in a mark of respect usually reserved 
for the emperor 
it was a war that cost japan dearly but also in the perverse 
way of history to come rewarded the loser it brought japan 
democracy in a constitution written by americans in three weeks a 
document that renounced war and included an article guaranteeing 
equal rights to women which americans have yet to see in their own 
constitution 
in the immediate postwar years it was uncle sam who fed japan 
and brought a rebirth of its smoldering industry with dollars and 
direction it was a group of american businessmen headed by joseph 
dodge a banker from detroit yes detroit who told the japanese 
they had to cut inflation build exports limit domestic 
consumption put a lid on wages improve productivity and close 
plants that couldnt compete 
it was the constitution written by americans that denied japan 
an army navy and air force and freed its economy to grow 
unfettered by military costs it was american bombs that flattened 
japanese factories and made totally new ones inevitable which 
brought new technology and new efficiency unmatched by the old 
plants in detroit and gary ind finally it was the war in korea 
that brought japan more billions as a base and supplier 
little or none of this can be credited to uncle sams big heart 
his interest lay with a strong stable japan on his side of the 
cold war 
and there japan remained while its economy grew at twice the 
speed of uncles and produced and sold more automobiles more ships 
and more television sets than any country in the world including 
the homeland of henry ford 
for a country that once wanted to live alone and be left alone 
japan has proven spectacularly gregarious the global reach of its 
investors now promises to replace the british empire in the old 
cliche about where the sun never sets 
sony buys columbia pictures mitsubishi is getting cozy with 
daimlerbenz and bringing together the descendants of the folks who 
used to build japanese fighters and german tanks japanese money is 
showing up in the shadows of 7eleven stores nippon television 
network pays for the restoration of michelangelos sistine chapel 
in exchange for exclusive film and tv rights japanese investors 
help finance donald trumps taj mahal in atlantic city 
japanese tourists line up solemnly to see the sunken battleships at 
the pearl harbor memorial while others play golf on courses owned 
by the japanese in hawaii 
</TEXT>
