<TEXT>
the story of a tragic love set against the moody backdrop of the 
louisiana territory is told by the artist annelouis 
girodettriosen in the funeral of atala 
the haunting oil painted around 1811 has been acquired by the 
high museum of art in atlanta this particular canvas there are 
three known versions was commissioned by the empress josephine 
wife of napoleon i for the chateau de malmaison 
the artist who was known as girodet based his work on 
atala a popular novel of the day written by francois rene de 
chateaubriand published in 1801 it told the story of chactas a 
natchez indian who was captured by an enemy tribe and condemned to 
death atala the captive wife of the tribes chie falls in love 
with chactas and helps him escape 
they wander the wilderness together not giving in to physical 
passions because atala had taken a vow of chastity rather than 
risk temptation she poisons herself and dies 
girodets neoclassical oil depicts her burial she is lowered 
half clothed with folded hands across her belly into a grave 
while a tortured chactas hugs her knees 
when the painting was first shown at the salon of 1808 it was 
enormously popular josephine liked it so much that she immediately 
commissioned a copy 
the original hangs in the louvre a small study for the painting 
hangs in the j paul getty museum in malibu calif 
