<DOCNO> AP900430-0199 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
patricia volk writes fiction and nonfiction 
often at the same time 
she calls her short stories riffs narratives proudly made 
up as she goes along but even volk knows you cant avoid injecting 
a little truth in fiction thats why she tears out pages from the 
newspapers and circles articles of interest just in case 
one day for instance she read about syzygy which means 
the earth sun and moon are in rare alignment months later 
syzygy became the title of a story included in her collection 
all it takes 1795 atheneum 
i was writing this story and i had a character press up 
against her exlover for the last time and i thought oh my god 
this is like syzygy every part connects explained volk 
and i thought where is that article i wondered whether 
people could line up like planets and i started rewriting it from 
that most of my characters are struggling for some kind of 
alignment but they cant find a syzygy its very rare that you 
can 
volk whose essays appear frequently in the new york times 
wrote the novel white light 
she can turn anything into a story thats how the manhattan 
resident became a writer ten years ago there was an incident at 
the playground with one of her two children and she couldnt stop 
describing it to friends before long the story was so polished 
volk decided to put it into writing 
i tell people all the time that the only difference between 
those who sell and those who dont sell are those who dont send it 
out she said some of the best writers dont send their work 
out theyre afraid of rejection its too much trouble theyre 
not sure they like it 
volk cant resist applying a little creativity to real life 
the stain from a spilled cup of coffee gets a little bigger that 
delay on the subway becomes a little longer encounters with 
strangers keep getting more interesting 
your memory plays tricks on you volk said any incident 
is like rashomon play that coffee spill back and its entirely 
different i think i bring a lot of fiction writing to the essay in 
terms of taking leaps and nuance i think of something that might 
distort it but it gives it a personal feel 
volks characters are often in danger of losing their lives in 
thought trying to impose order on events as logical as the daily 
horoscope in reckless dreamer a woman reflects on the 
personality of her former lover 
he was an editor and lived the most censurious life she knew 
he criticized things other people never thought about labels on 
cans the wording on menus how people sat he even criticized her 
syntax and her dreams if shed stayed with him he would have 
criticized her into the ground 
in which is better del analyzes everything from sex to 
lemonade thinks too much but cant for the life of her stop is 
included in a list of things she doesnt like about herself 
in the title story of all it takes lucy is so unhappy that 
she writes letters to the artist georgia okeeffe seeking advice 
from an expert on the meaning of life 
i think my characters are straddling a fence volk said 
on one side theyre powerless and on the other side theyre 
rationalists theyre trying to make sense of things 
lucy is really quite on the edge shes trying to maintain her 
equilibrium with those letters to georgia okeeffe but when youre 
needy and youre feeling terribly you look for answers in 
everything if its a painter and you move yourself to bounce 
ideas off a dead person fine 
volk who grew up in manhattan and long island had plenty time 
to think as a child when her older sister was born her 
grandfather quit his job to spend time with the baby fortunately 
volk says her birth was less eventful 
secondborn children are different less is expected of them 
and less time is devoted to them its a very nurturing thing for a 
writer because theres less time physically for you you dont have 
that intensity beamed on you 
she worked full time with writing squeezed in during lunch 
hours but volk made the best of it managing to compose 11 drafts 
of white light with the help of daily trips to a nearby coffee 
shop 
id get the coffee id get the egg salad and the cheese and 
id go to the library and it was so wonderful she recalled 
the whole process was like anne tyler sharpening her pencils 
before she crosses the threshhold into the room where she writes 
having quit her job and with the kids in school volk can write 
all the time now the routine is simple just grab a cup of coffee 
sit down and get to work but writing remains mysterious what 
volk might call a yellow banana something that doesnt turn 
out the way its expected 
writing the essay i kind of know what i think up front and i 
can ask questions of my reader but i dont know what i think up 
front at all writing fiction 
its a real kind of discovery process for me i do it with the 
unsensitive part of my brain the sensitive part of my brain comes 
later when i try to make sense of things 
</TEXT>
