<TEXT>
friends of broccoli saddened by george 
bushs dislike of it can get a lift from another president thomas 
jefferson master gardener as well as author of the declaration of 
independence grew numerous varieties 
broccolis green purple white appear repeatedly in 
gardening notes jefferson kept throughout his life showing he was 
planting the vegetable in his own kitchen garden at monticello in 
virginia and exchanging seeds with friends 
broccoli aside anyone looking for a patron saint of gardening 
will find the perfect model in jefferson who said no occupation 
is so delightful to me as the culture of the earth and no culture 
comparable to that of the garden 
jefferson lived to age 83 statesman inventor architect 
astronomer founder of the university of virgina but despite his 
myriad activities he had time for a garden diary starting with an 
entry dated march 30 1766 when he was 22 purple hyacinth 
begins to bloom 
the burdens of the presidency did not stop him on april 6 
1804 for example he wrote sowed seeds of the east india 
asparagus in small bed sometimes he jotted garden notes on odd 
sheets of paper 
in 1808 his last year in the white house jefferson wrote to a 
