to man it is next to the most precious perhaps it may claim a 
preference even to bread because there is such an infinitude of 
vegetables which it renders a proper and comfortable nourishment 
intimate views of jefferson as gardener and farmer in his old 
age also are contained in jefferson and his time the sage of 
monticello little brown and co 1981 the sixth and final 
volume of dumas malones epic biography his previous volumes won 
the pulitzer prize for history in 1975 
the books tell us jefferson collected seeds everywhere county 
neighbors nurserymen naturalists from a friend in italy even 
from gen lafayettes aunt mrs smith who was the wife of the 
publisher of the national intelligencer visited him in his 
retirment and reported he kept his vegetable seeds in a little 
closet peas and beans were in tin canisters she said but all the 
other seeds were little phials labeled and hung on little 
hooks everything being in the neatest order 
as the years went on jefferson suffered from rheumatism but 
his spirit was not dampened as he said but though an old man i 
am but a young gardener 
</TEXT>
