<DOCNO> AP900430-0227 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a recent london stock exchange rule change that 
allows for a delay in reporting large trades is anticompetitive 
the office of fair trading said monday 
sir gordon borrie directorgeneral of fair trading said the 
24hour delay in reporting large deals deprives the market of 
information that could affect the price of stocks 
it also gives trading opportunities to those market makers 
involved in the deals which are denied to their competitors borrie 
said 
the exchange decided in early 1989 to postpone the reporting of 
trades of over 100000 pounds or 164000 until 24 hours after 
completion of the transaction 
market makers had complained that instantaneous publication of 
large share deals on the stock exchange automated quotation system 
spoiled liquidity and led to volatility in share prices 
borrie said he had not uncovered any evidence that liquidity was 
affected or that the delay reduced volatility 
the directorgeneral sent his report to trade secretary nicholas 
ridley to decide what action if any the government should take 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

