<TEXT>
the federal environmental protection 
agency plans to let automakers keep counting big gasgulping cars 
as imports no matter where the car is assembled epa 
administrator william reilly said monday 
general motors corp and ford motor co have used the provision 
to raise their domestic corporate average fuel economy or cafe by 
changing the manufacturing site of some major components in large 
cars and counting them as part of the companys import fleet 
i dont wish to signal any substantive change in approach on 
cafe at this time reilly said at a news conference before 
addressing the economic club of detroit 
domestic and import fleets are counted separately under cafe 
regulations the amount of domestically made components determines 
if a car is counted in the domestic or import fleet 
for instance ford planned last year to make the 1991 models of 
its ford crown victoria and mercury grand marquis built in st 
thomas ontario count in the companys domestic cafe fleet as 
their domestic content dropped below 75 percent 
such a switch would have made it easier for fords domestic 
fleet to meet cafe regulations by increasing the percentage of more 
fuelefficient cars on its domestic fleet fords imported cars far 
surpassed cafe requirements leaving room for the less 
fuelefficient cars 
ford spokesman dick judy said monday those plans changed and for 
now the cars remain in the domestic cafe column 
the current cafe standard is 275 mpg for both fleets 
reilly was in town for two days of meetings with automotive 
industry executives officials of the united auto workers union and 
epa officials in ann arbor where the agency operates its motor 
vehicle emissions laboratory 
during the news conference and in a speech to the economic club 
reilly pitched the bush administrations clean air proposals and 
praised an oil companys plan to buy for 700 each cars made 
before 1971 when the government began regulating tailpipe emissions 
the faster you replace the older cars with new ones the 
faster youll clean up the air he said however reilly added 
that addition measures are needed to cut tailpipe emissions because 
so many new cars have been added to the highways and cars are being 
driven more 
automakers have balked at further cutting emissions saying that 
it would be very expensive while yielding only minor pollution 
decreases 
