<TEXT>
michael milken may be entitled to a tax break on 
at least part of 400 million the fallen junk bond king is placing 
in a government fund to compensate injured investors legal experts 
said monday 
such a deduction may appear startling for an admitted felon 
milken pleaded guilty last week to six criminal securities and tax 
law violations but it could be perfectly legal under internal 
revenue service guidelines 
under his settlement of civil and criminal charges the former 
drexel burnham lambert inc executive agreed to pay 200 million in 
fines and 400 million in restitution for investors who can prove 
they were defrauded by his activities 
presuming that milken has reported his income faithfully and 
complied with federal income tax laws and no one says he hasnt 
he already has paid taxes on the 400 million 
milken in effect would be returning money that never belonged to 
him but on which he has paid uncle sam tax experts said 
thats not too shocking said marvin a chirelstein a 
columbia university tax law professor it just reverses the tax 
consequences it puts the situation where its as if it had not 
happened 
according to court papers milken made 11 billion from 1983 to 
1987 his advisers claim he paid nearly onehalf of the amount in 
taxes milkens net worth has been estimated by fortune magazine at 
12 billion 
under the irs tax code civil or criminal defendants are not 
allowed to deduct fines or penalties paid to the government for 
breaking the law milkens 200 million fine to the us treasury 
falls under that provision 
but the code generally allows deductions for the payment of 
compensatory damages as well as fees or expenses incurred in a 
legal defense which can be considered part of normal business 
operations 
however if the government could prove that the money being 
returned was obtained by violating some sharply defined public 
policy that would open the door to preventing a tax deduction 
experts said 
how big a tax break might occur well assuming milken is in the 
highest tax bracket the total could amount to a third of the 
restitution fund about 133 million no one involved in the case 
believes that will happen 
but the public appearance that milken was getting a good deal at 
taxpayers expense might be less than flattering for government 
prosecutors who arranged the plea bargain 
new york tax attorney michael saltzman said the argument against 
a deduction would be its supposed to be part of the punishment 
why would the government be picking up a part of that 
no claims have been made against the money by the irs milken 
doesnt even have to fork over the 400 million until 60 days after 
his scheduled oct 1 sentencing how much actually gets paid out 
might not be resolved for years 
the restitution fund settles allegations by the securities and 
exchange commission that included insider trading and other frauds 
not included in the criminal plea bargain any investor claim is 
eligible for a piece of the fund 
under the terms of the settlement any money not dished out to 
investors after seven years will be turned over to the treasury 
and presumably could then be classified as a fine which would not 
be deductible 
it seems to me in milkens interest to see that as much of 
that gets paid out to those who justifiably lay claim to damage 
said tax attorney lawrence feld chairman of an american bar 
association panel on civil and criminal tax penalties 
an irs spokesman said the law is not clear on what tax 
consequences might arise in cases where restitution is not 
earmarked for a particular individual the spokesman who asked not 
to be named declined to discuss the milken case a spokesman for 
milken also declined to comment 
barry goldsmith sec desputy chief litigation counsel said tax 
deductibility was not a factor in the milken settlement our job 
is to get the money he said 
</TEXT>
