<TEXT>
the belzberg family of canada claimed 
monday to have won a seat on the board of armstrong world 
industries inc the company that prompted pennsylvanias tough new 
antitakeover law 
the disclosure came at the armstrongs annual shareholders 
meeting just three days after the state enacted the law designed to 
stymie corporate raiders 
armstrong chairman william h adams said he was confident at 
least three of the four incumbent board members seeking reelection 
were retained 
he acknowledged the possibility that the belzbergs had landed 
one spot on the 13member board but added it would take until at 
least may 11 to get a final vote tally 
the belzbergs own a 107 percent stake in armstrong they have 
waged a proxy fight to seat four directors and change company rules 
to weaken the boards authority to block a hostile takeover 
the state law which took effect immediately is intended to 
discourage corporate raiders by seizing profits from a takeover 
attempt restricting voting rights and preserving labor contracts 
if corporate ownership changes hands 
the law was drafted last year after the belzbergs declared an 
interest in armstrong which makes flooring and building materials 
armstrong management has declined to meet with the belzbergs 
the family has criticized the company for supporting the 
antitakeover law and accused management of working against 
shareholder interests 
armstrong has characterized the belzbergs as inept managers who 
have driven companies virtually into the ground compromising 
shareholder earnings 
addressing the meeting adams said the antitakeover law would 
not alter the companys relationship with stockholders but would 
deter raiders who want to line their own pockets 
adams said the board had adopted a policy ensuring that 
stockholder interests would not be supplanted by other constituents 
the action apparently stems from concerns about the 
antitakeover law which allows management to put the interests of 
employees suppliers or the community above shareholders in making 
corporate decisions including weighing takeover bids 
during the meeting adams was questioned by only one 
stockholder who asked how much the company had spent promoting the 
antitakeover bill adams said he did not have an exact figure but 
that it would be under 500000 
when asked why the directors had not met with the belzbergs he 
said the past operating practices of the belzbergs were not 
encouraging us to meet with them 
the proposed changes to the companys bylaws have been held up 
in a court challenge and were not on the agenda but the company 
took a nonbinding vote to gauge shareholder sentiment the issue 
could be revisited pending the outcome of the suit 
one proposal would allow a shareholder or group owning 20 
percent or more of the stock to call special shareholder meetings 
the company says shareholders can ask the board to call meetings 
at its discretion 
representatives of first city diversified inc a belzberg 
entity said they believed the changes would pass overwhelmingly 
it was not clear when or if the vote would be released 
first citys assertion that it had seated michael c jensen a 
harvard business school professor on the armstrong board was based 
on its owning more than 10 percent of the companys stock in 
addition to proxies it solicited officials said 
other belzberg nominees were richard e bennett chairman of 
scovill inc greta e marshall general partner of the marshall 
plan and a former investment manager for the california public 
employees retirement system and frederick r warrenboulton a 
resident scholar at the american enterprise institute 
the incumbent board members seeking reelection were barbara 
hackman franklin of washington dc joseph l jones of lancaster 
robert f patton of pittsburgh and harry k wells of towson md 
</TEXT>
