<TEXT>
a supreme court decision that states and 
individuals have the power to challenge completed mergers on 
anticompetitive grounds isnt likely to arouse a storm of attacks 
on other done deals experts said monday 
enforcement authorities appreciate the business world just 
cant function if transactions can be challenged five and 10 years 
later said georgetown university law professor robert pitofsky 
after the nations highest court said it would allow california 
officials to try to block the merger of the alpha beta and lucky 
grocery store chains 
but the 90 ruling monday nonetheless was expected to inject 
another note of caution into the already wary takeover market 
the supreme court said any opponent of a merger and not just 
the federal government has the right to sue to force the 
divestiture of merged businesses the decision does not negate the 
merger of alpha beta and lucky it sends the case back to court in 
california where state officials must still prove at trial that 
the deal should be blocked 
pitofsky said california sought to block the merger because 
state officials did not get the support they wanted from the 
federal government which had approved the 25 billion acquisition 
of lucky stores inc by alpha betas parent american stores co 
in 1988 
california officials contend that if the companies 600 stores 
in the state are combined consumers would end up paying 440 
million extra each year because of reduced competition and higher 
prices 
despite californias victory lawrence j white a professor at 
the stern graduate school of business at new york university said 
i dont think it is going to mean a grand unlocking of deals 
walter adams an economics professor at michigan state 
university agreed there wouldnt be a flood of litigation to undo 
done deals but he said its possible that some alreadycompleted 
mergers will be challenged on a casebycase basis 
in addition antitrust experts said future deals likely will 
face more scrutiny 
what this does is make the states a major player in mergers 
said pitofsky 
adams said the state attorneys general have been extremely 
active to the extent that they legally could in opposing the merger 
wave and mondays ruling gives local officials more ammunition 
but the decision could have a chilling effect on dealmakers 
themselves forcing them to think twice about proposing a buyout or 
merger that they know could run afoul of state officials 
this in itself may do a great deal to slow down the merger 
movement adams predicted 
adams said a more aggressive stance on antitrust enforcement by 
the bush administration following the more lenient reagan era could 
be behind the supreme courts decision 
the cop on the beat is no longer looking the other way he 
said 
the monday ruling by the high court was likely to further slow 
the takeover business which has been dealt a series of blows over 
the past year on friday for example the pennsylvania legislature 
enacted the toughest antitakeover law in the country 
perhaps more important the collapse of the junk bond market 
last fall has denied takeover investors access to enormous amounts 
of money for acquisitions 
the risky highyield bonds which fueled the takeover boom of 
the 1980s fell out of favor when the 67 billion debtfinanced 
buyout of federated department stores inc faltered in september 
without junk bonds takeover activity has dropped off 
considerably 
</TEXT>
