the supreme court on monday refused to kill a 
lawsuit against general motors corp stemming from what a lower 
court called the highly charged environment of largescale 
layoffs 
the court without comment let stand rulings that the fraud and 
misrepresentation suit by 32 former employees of a gm subsidiary in 
clinton miss should go to trial 
those who sued had been employed at a packard electric plant in 
clinton before gm in 1983 began laying off hundreds of workers 
there in response to sluggish demand for domestic automobiles 
in other action the court 
gave state governments and consumers a potential pocketbook 
victory by ruling unanimously in a california case that they may 
use federal antitrust law to break up corporate mergers 
let the government force thousands of transportation department 
employees to take random drug tests the court without comment 
rejected arguments that such tests violate privacy rights 
requested the bush administrations views about oklahomas 
attempt to collect a sales tax on cigarettes and other items sold 
at a convenience store owned and run by an indian tribe the court 
said it wants to know what justice department lawyers think about a 
ruling that bars the imposition of such a tax 
agreed to settle a bankruptcy dispute stemming from a fraud 
lawsuit against a kansas city mo businessman the court said it 
will hear an appeal by two men who sued the businessman and are 
trying to collect a 525000 judgment the case turns on what 
standard of evidence applies 
cargiant gm negotiated a separation agreement with the 
employees union under which workers could opt for a severance 
payment instead of having their seniority and rehire rights 
preserved 
under the socalled voluntary termination of employment plan 
the 32 packard electric employees received payments of between 
10000 and 22000 when leaving their jobs 
their suit alleges that at meetings to explain the severance 
plan a gm representative said they could be rehired if new jobs 
were created the employees allegedly were told they would have to 
apply like everyone else without any consideration of seniority 
but would be eligible for rehiring 
new positions opened at the plant in 1985 but the 32 
exemployees were told the severance plan they had chosen made them 
ineligible for rehiring 
the 32 employees sued in federal court but based their suit on 
mississippi law claims of fraud and misrepresentation 
lawyers for gm sought a dismissal arguing that the proper forum 
was the national labor relations board even if a court suit were 
allowed gm said the state law claims would be preempted by 
federal labor law 
a federal trial judge and the 5th us circuit court of appeals 
ruled against gm 
the appeals court said the nlrb had no jurisdiction in the case 
it characterized the case as one involving alleged promises made 
and broken in the highly charged environment of largescale layoffs 
and shifts in the labor market 
gm then sought supreme court review 
while the original suit named 32 plaintiffs jackson attorney 
richard roberts iii said it has been expanded to include about 50 
former employees 
were delighted roberts said of the supreme court ruling 
we look forward to proceeding with the lawsuit 
he said a trial date was not immediately scheduled and refused 
to comment on whether he was discussing a settlement with gm 
lawyers 
john maciarz a gm spokesman in detroit were obviously 
disappointed but the case has never been tried on its merits 
