<TEXT>
the boeing co which is selling more planes and 
making more on them said monday its sales jumped 60 percent and 
its profits 87 percent in the first quarter of 1990 
company officials said demand should remain high for boeings 
jetliners and hinted strongly they would go ahead with their 
planned new jet the 777 but they warned shareholders at their 
annual meeting to expect another losing year for boeings troubled 
defense and space segments 
boeing announced a threefortwo stock split the second year in 
a row it has done so 
shareholders gave directors permission to issue more stock but 
rejected a request that boeing stop doing business with south 
africa despite efforts by a baptist minister who camped in a 
plywood shack in front of company headquarters for three days and 
urged holders to do the right thing they also turned down 
three shareholders rights resolutions including a call for a 
shareholder vote on the companys poison pill plan 
boeing earned 302 million or 131 a share on sales of 64 
billion for the first three months of 1990 compared with profits 
of 161 million or 70 cents a share on sales of 4 billion in the 
first quarter of 1989 
the 1989 figures are before a restatement to reflect a change in 
accounting for income taxes which produced a onetime gain of 298 
million or 129 a share with the gain earnings in the 1989 
quarter were 459 million or 199 a share 
boeing was left with a number of nearly complete planes when 
production was virtually stopped by a 48day machinists union 
strike last fall as a result it was able to deliver 84 jets in 
the first quarter compared with 67 in firstquarter 1989 
deliveries included 22 747400 jumbo jets boeings largest and 
most expensive plane worth about 125 million each just five 747s 
were delivered in the first quarter of 1989 when boeing was 
struggling to introduce the newmodel 747400 
frank shrontz chairman and chief executive officer said the 
higher profits resulted from increased sales and improved operating 
margins on commercial jets higher federal taxes and losses in 
other segments of the company partially offset that performance he 
said 
last year boeings military and space divisions lost 474 
million boeing has bid aggressively on defense and space contracts 
in recent years and fallen behind on several programs at the 
beginning of the year it consolidated its military work into 
boeing defense and space group to try to make the segments more 
efficient 
shrontz said progress had been made but continuing technical 
cost and schedule problems would result in another operating loss 
in 1990 
boeing didnt release figures on how large the defense loss 
might be but george shapiro analyst with solomon brothers in new 
york said his estimate was about 150 million to 200 million 
boeing is coming to the end of some troublesome programs such 
as the longdelayed new air force one jets and isnt getting any 
new programs that could cause further losses shapiro said 
last week defense secretary dick cheney proposed cutting or 
delaying two key programs for boeing the b2 stealth bomber and 
the advanced tactical fighter boeing is a major subcontractor on 
the b2 with 10000 employees assigned to the project and is 
competing for the multibillion dollar contract for the air forces 
newgeneration warplane 
dan pinick defense and space group president said watershed 
events in the soviet union and eastern europe have led boeing to 
anticipate a 5 percent decline in the defense department budget 
through 1995 
clearly we dont know exactly what the future budget levels 
will be but given the recent events we believe that we should make 
business decisions based on a more conservative estimate pinick 
said 
dean thornton president of boeing commercial airplane group 
got to deliver a much cheerier speech noting that 57 customers 
ordered 963 boeing planes worth 475 billion last year the fifth 
straight year of record orders thornton remarked were getting 
to numbers that i cant hardly relate to 
boeing has cranked up its production rate from 24 planes a month 
in 1988 to 28 in 1989 and plans to be at 34 a month later this 
year thornton said by mid1991 the rate will be 38 month he 
said and boeing is considering going to 41 a month in 1992 
in addition to increasing production on current programs we 
plan to introduce the new 777 airplane in that time frame 
thornton said 
boeing hasnt officially launched the 777 a twoengine widebody 
that would carry 350 passengers but has been talking with airlines 
and firming up its design no airlines have announced orders for it 
yet but shrontz told reporters the company hoped to have reached 
a quantity that would allow us to launch it by midyear 
boeing had a firm backlog of 841 billion in unfilled orders as 
of march 31 compared with 806 billion at the end of 1989 all 
but 8 percent of that was for commercial customers 
</TEXT>
