<TEXT>
the chairman of wells fargo bank predicted 
that troubles at the nations banks and thrifts will force a 
radical restructuring and consolidation of the financial services 
industry 
reform radical structural reform is the only sane 
alternative the banker carl reichardt said monday its the 
only safe road 
he predicted that reform eventually would establish a single 
regulatory body to oversee the industry and remove competitive 
barriers between banks securities firms and insurance companies 
reichardt who made his remarks before a gathering of the 
society of american business editors and writers said the 
resolution trust corp established last year to oversee the 
bailout of the thrift industry has a daunting task 
the job will entail giving many sick savings and loans a 
decent burial while trying to preserve as much value as possible 
in selling off what reichardt called a motley collection of 
assets 
complicating the effort are the rtcs byzantine 
organizational chart and the 371page law that governs its work 
reichardt said he called potential buyers bottom fishers who 
are the shrewdest buyers in the country 
he urged banks to improve credit quality and chastised big banks 
for failing to have credit training programs he said that was akin 
to trying to run an engineering company with poets 
as in so many industries the opportunities lie in executing 
the basics well he concluded 
earlier john f mcdonnell chairman of mcdonnell douglas corp 
said booming orders for commercial aircraft and new markets in 
space will help the aerospace industry weather cuts in defense 
spending 
the us defense budget does not represent a vein of gold to 
be mined for social programs mcdonnell conceded 
rather developments in eastern europe and elsewhere represent 
enormous potential for increased commercial aviation as tourism and 
business opportunities grow he said 
defense cuts have renewed enthusiasm for space exploration and 
transportation mcdonnell said adding that prospects in this 
part of our business are looking better than at any time since the 
1960s 
the recent layoff of 3000 workers by the douglas aircraft unit 
in long beach calif was not a retrenchment mcdonnell said 
some workers will be transferred and others were let go because 
they did not have the necessary skills but the overall picture 
remains healthy he said adding that the division hired 10000 
workers last year 
